<br>
The class that got hurt the most by these changes, were the Mages.  A close friend of mine is a 58 mage, and these changes were uncalled for imho in the &quot;current game&quot;.  But if you're thinking ahead, as SoE *gasp* seems to be doing at this point in time.  It was done to make the Lower end PoP encounters within reach of the &quot;smaller guys&quot; by making them 3-4 group encounters, but to still make them challenging.  The new large scale encounters will have to use different tactics, but will probably still encourage relatively large numbers with a reasonable base of healing power.<br>
<br>
As for the Manaburn nerf, as much as I wish they hadn't changed it, It was something that should have been done.<br>
When there was 10 burners on our server, problems were minimal and the new things were challenging.  But as time passes and the Wizard population matures, I'm positive things would have gotten bad on our server.  <br>
<br>
Manaburn itself loses much of its functionality, Sure you can throw a big nuke on something, but without the ability to combine it with 1 or 2 more burners, it becomes pointless on raid situations.  On a large encounter (200k+), all of the wizzies would burn within the first 15 seconds of the fight if it was a non-gater.  That gave you plenty of time to med / robe / rod up to a reasonable amount of mana to resume nuking at the 40-50% mark of the said MoB.  On a large scale encounter where the MoB can gate, Manaburn could play an important role to stop that gate. Jorllaeg and Harla Dar come to mind, If you wait until the mob is a 4-6% life, and simultaneously burn, the Mob *can't* gate.  <br>
<br>
Oh well, seems thats all old history now - Time for new tactics!<br>
